        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Augusta Ga.</placeName>
                <date>21st Apr. 5626</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Since my last, the “Occident,” from<lb/> the commencement of the
                present volume, has reached<lb/> me by mail. In the <date>June</date> No. I notice
                some very<lb/> kind remarks about me, which claim my earnest<lb/> thanks.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have obtained two more subscribers<lb/> from <persName>Mrs
                    Mordercai Hyams</persName> &amp; <persName>Mr Morris Cohen</persName>, to<lb/>
                whom please forward the Nos. from No. 1 of the current year.<lb/> I shall continue
                my endeavors to promote the circulation<lb/> of the Occident in this city,
                    <del>the</del> but I apprehend I have<lb/> pretty much touched the limits.
                Possibly I may yet be<lb/> able to influence one or two more.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am laboring diligently in the little<lb/> field in which I now
                find myself, where I must confess<lb/> I do not find Religion or Knowing as I could
                desire. Mam-<lb/>mon has stronger claims, &amp; greater influence than
                    <sic>Adonay</sic>.<lb/> “'Tis true 'tis pity, and pity 'tis 'tis true.”Again, I
                perceive<lb/> a tendency among several to go astray after the strange god,<lb/>
                which you have characteristically termed “the modern hybrid,”</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>but as long as I remain here, I am determined it shall<lb/> make no headway, by
                following the simple rule. Withstand<lb/> at the beginning. This for your uneducated
                eye. Our<lb/> friend of the Messenger went a step too far in publishing<lb/> a
                private letter to him, which annoyed me a little, tho<lb/> the matter was hardly
                worth notice. At the breaking out<lb/> of the War, he became so political and
                violent in his crusade against<lb/> the <placeName>South</placeName> that I
                abandoned the agency of the paper and<lb/> even my continuance as a subscriber in a
                letter which<lb/> was rather caustic. With the return of peace, I wished to<lb/>
                remit him the subscription which I owed, and at same<lb/> time to introduce a
                gentleman from <placeName>Augusta</placeName> who <del>wished</del><lb/> required
                some Tallethoth, and whilst doing so, in the <sic>fulness</sic><lb/> of my heart,
                and in deference to his years and long services<lb/> I held out freely the olive
                branch. He ought to have drawn<lb/> the deliberate line of demarcation between this,
                and the<lb/> topics I added on general Jewish making here. However<lb/>
                <add>מה שעבר עבר</add> It is hardly worth notice indeed.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">With kind regards, participated in<lb/> by <persName>Mrs
                    Jacobs</persName>, believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">yours faithfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">Henry S. Jacobs</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
